ACTOR Sello Maake Ka Ncube is over the moon that his play, The Voice, is returning for the second time. The play inspired by the rise in cases of gender-based violence was meant to be performed only during the 16 Days of Activism in December, but was high in demand and has been brought back. It was first staged at the Joburg Theatre, and will return from 27 to 30 January at Soweto Theatre in Jabulani, Soweto. Sello, who recently celebrated 40 years in the entertainment industry, took to social media to express his joy about the return of the show. “After a successful run at the Joburg Theatre and due to public demand, The Voice is moving to The Red Room, Soweto Theatre from 27 to 30 January. “Recently, this GBV awareness production was on for two consecutive days at Joburg Theatre and both performances were sold out.” ALSO READ : WATCH: ISANDLWANA WALK BY ACTOR MBUSO KHOZA He also explained what the play was about. “A theatre piece with a predominantly female cast highlights the plight of women who have survived abuse, domestic violence, discrimination, and exclusion and is a clarion call for men to take note and be at the centre of eradicating GBV, dubbed as the shadow pandemic of RSA by the president. “This play, produced by Sello Maake KaNcube Foundation, aims to create a 365-day GBV awareness campaign using inventive methods invocation of self-redemption in men of all races of our the country,” said Sello. A post shared by Official SELLO Maake kaNcube (@sellomkn) 